###Question 1:
In the swallows dataset, each row is a breeding female tree swallow and the columns tell you her brightness, which treatment she was in, her brood size, and her breeding success. There are two ways to consider breeding success: either as a binary did she fledge any young or not? encoded in the success column, or by considering the number of nestlings that lived and died per female (nestlings_lived and nestlings_died columns).

1a. Create a plot of the proportion of successful breeders in the predation group and in the control group.

swallows %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = treatment, fill = as.factor(success))) + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill")

# another option if we just want to visualize success:
swallows %>% 
group_by(treatment) %>% 
summarize(proportion = mean(success)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x= treatment, y = proportion)) + 
  geom_col()

Sabrinas notes: Number of fledglings per nest is something that might feel pretty poisson-y. Again, beause I know its never poisson, Im going to use a relative, in this case quasipoisson. In this case, when we look at the mean vs.var of nestlings_lived, its not that over-dispersed. But, theres no real harm here in using an alternative.

One other thing to maybe note: in cases like this we may run into whats called zero inflated data. Thats when we have more zeros than wed expect, for example, because some biological process is generating complete nest failures (like predation). Then, a separate process generates variation fledging success among those nests pass the baseline of not failing. There are some other packages that are useful for modeling zero inflated data and other flavors of not-poisson. But save that for another day

Semi-important note I didnt say in class:

It is very hard to calculate p values for LMMs because its hard to decide what the dfs are. Our rule of thumb is that dfs = N - number of estimated parameters. But what is N for a mixed model? It is not the number of nestlings (because of pseudoreplication), and its not exactly number of nests either (because we do have more information in our data set). Its somewhere in the middle.

In order to extract P values, you have to make a decision about these dfs, and lme4 wont do it on its own, because it does require some assumptions and is somewhat subjective. What lmerTest does is chooses a way to get a P value (the Satterthwaite method) and it runs it. But the writers of lmer4 didnt want you sail by that point and they wanted you to realize its not trivial. In practice, using lmerTest is fairly common, and if you were using another stats program (SPSS etc.) in the fine print youd read that theyre also using an approximation of some sort to get to the p vals for LMM.

Super annoying and concerning error:

Ive been trying to force myself to use the native pipe |> instead of the tidyverse pipe %>% recently because it seems like the new cool thing. However, I just found an example of where the |> pipe throws an unexpected error:

# New pipe
nestlings |> 
  mutate (fledge_numeric = as.numeric(as.factor(nestling_fate))) |>
  lm(fledge_numeric ~ treatment, data = _) # destination indicated by _

# Old pipe
nestlings |> 
  mutate (fledge_numeric = as.numeric(as.factor(nestling_fate))) %>%
  lm(fledge_numeric ~ treatment, data = .) # destination indicated by .

Thanks to google I realized that if you want to set a destination for your piped object in old piping you use . and in new piping you use _. So thats super annoying to me but now we know. It also appears that %>% can do a few things that |> cannot. Read more here: https://www.tidyverse.org/blog/2023/04/base-vs-magrittr-pipe/ It is generally good practice to use Base R functions when you can, because dependencies make things more complicated. However, ymmv with pipes- do what makes sense for your workflow.

# See if a random slope will work. I won't do it for year, bc only two years. 
# By putting "wing" in front of our random effects, we are asking R to say not only
# could the intercept (i.e. average mass) differ among sites and/or nests 
# But the relationship betwene wing and mass (i.e. the slope) may also 
# vary among sites and nests. 
mod2 <- lmer(mass ~ wing+ (1|year) + (wing|site/nest), data = nestlings)

Note, this does give a convergence warning (boundary (singular) fit). This error is common as your random effects become more complex. It doesnt mean that your model is wrong per se, but it does suggest that you dont have quite enough data to parameterize it. If you get a convergence error, common guidance is to simplify your random effects structure.

Final notes:

Random effects models can get tricky, especially when you start specifying slopes and intercepts, and especially if you get into the weeds of p values.

If this is your first rodeo with GLMs LMMS: Try to familiarize yourself with how the models run and how theyre interpreted. Try to understand when youd use a glm vs.a lmm, and how the syntax works. If you are having trouble with any of that talk to Sabrina.

If you feel pretty confident with GLMs LMMs: Expand your knowledge by reading up on some of the technical details and in-depth considerations

Ben Bolker is the LMM god, so read his stuff and listen to whatever he says on Stack Overflow. https://bbolker.github.io/mixedmodels-misc/glmmFAQ.html#what-are-the-p-values-listed-by-summaryglmerfit-etc.-are-they-reliable

Other stats peoples explanation of random effects: https://bookdown.org/steve_midway/DAR/random-effects.html https://m-clark.github.io/mixed-models-with-R/random_slopes.html
